            <div>
                <head>General Structure of SSK scenarios and steps</head>
                <p>The SSK offers researchers needing standardized methods and resources complete
                    frameworks to carry out their project, in Arts and Humanities and Heritage
                    science. It takes the form of step by step research scenarios where the use of
                    standards is clearly identified. Theses scenarios are divided into different
                    steps, implying specific tasks. Each step contains a set of bibliographical
                    resources. </p>
                <div>
                    <head>Main elements</head>
                    <p>The main elements of the SSK TEI are: <specList>
                            <specDesc key="listEvent"/>
                            <specDesc key="event"/>
                            <!-- to be replaced by linkGrp -->
                            <specDesc key="listRef"/>
                            <!--<specDesc key="linkGrp"/>-->
                            <specDesc key="ref"/>
                        </specList>
                    </p>
                    <p> A scenario is a list of events (<gi>listEvent</gi>), each scenario step is
                        an event (<gi>event</gi>). </p>
                    <p><gi>event</gi>, core element of the SSK scenario, is a full description of
                        the scenario step: <list>
                            <item>a label:<specList>
                                    <specDesc key="label"/>
                                </specList>
                            </item>
                            <item>a description: <specList>
                                    <specDesc key="desc"/>
                                </specList></item>
                            <item>some descriptive terms following controlled vocabularies: <specList>
                                    <specDesc key="term"/>
                                </specList></item>
                            <item>bibliographical references:<specList>
                                    <specDesc key="ref"/>
                                </specList></item>
                        </list> Events are stored in external files, allowing them to be used in
                        different scenarios. Scenario files gather <gi>event</gi> in a
                            <gi>listEvent</gi> element, by referencing them with a <att>ref</att>
                        attribute. It is however possible to modify the content of the event called
                        in a scenario, using the attribute <att>mode</att> (see below)</p>
                    <p> The resources consists of Bibliographical references. They are of two types
                        : “general resources” and “project specific”. These elements can be repeated
                        (one per "project"). At each level, the elements are enriched with keywords
                        that can be <gi>term</gi> or XML attributes.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <head>Common attributes</head>
                    <p>The attributes used by all the elements are: <list>
                            <item><att>xml:lang</att>. This attribute is mandatory in all the
                                content elements,namely <gi>label</gi>, <gi>desc</gi>,
                                <gi>term</gi>. The authoritative list of registered language subtags
                                is maintained by IANA and is available at <ref
                                    target="http://www.iana.org/assignments/language-subtag-registry"
                                    >http://www.iana.org/assignments/language-subtag-registry</ref>.
                                    <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                                    <label xml:lang="en">Create associated documentation</label>
                                    <label xml:lang="fr">Création de la documentation
                                        associée</label>
                                </egXML></item>
                            <item><att>mode</att>, available for all content elements. the
                                    <att>mode</att> is used in scenario files to allow for
                                modification of the steps imported. <egXML
                                    xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                                    <event xml:id="s1" type="step" ref="step_EaXswO_290517">
                                        <head mode="change">
                                            <!-- The new <label> replace the initial step label, in the declared language-->
                                            <label mode="change" xml:lang="jp">...</label>
                                            <!-- A new term is added to the step -->
                                            <term mode="add"/>
                                        </head> ... </event>
                                </egXML></item>
                            <item>the <att>type</att> attribute is required in most elements. See
                                below for details.</item>
                        </list>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div>
                <head>Description of SSK TEI elements</head>
                <div>
                    <head>Scenarios</head>
                    <p>The scenario is represented by the element <gi>listEvent</gi>, containing a
                        set of <gi>event</gi> elements, references to external TEI files.</p>

                    <div>
                        <head>Header</head>
                        <p>The structure of the Scenario header is as follows:</p>
                        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                            <TEI type="scenario">
                                <teiHeader>
                                    <fileDesc>
                                        <titleStmt>

                                            <title><!-- Title of the tei document, not title of the scenario --></title>
                                            <author>
                                                <persName>...</persName>
                                                <affiliation>...</affiliation>
                                            </author>
                                        </titleStmt>
                                        <publicationStmt>
                                            <authority>Parthenos ...</authority>
                                            <availability>
                                                <licence
                                                  target="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">
                                                  <p>The Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 Unported
                                                  (CC BY 4.0) Licence applies to this document.</p>
                                                </licence>
                                            </availability>
                                        </publicationStmt>
                                        <sourceDesc>
                                            <p>Created from scratch</p>
                                        </sourceDesc>
                                    </fileDesc>
                                    <revisionDesc>
                                        <change>
                                            <!-- Only for major changes: addition of an author, of a step, etc. -->
                                        </change>
                                    </revisionDesc>
                                </teiHeader> ... </TEI>
                        </egXML>
                        <p>The scenario header includes the following data elements: <list
                                type="unordered">
                                <item>the title of the document (which is not the title of the
                                    scenario)</item>
                                <item>the authors of the scenarios</item>
                                <item>the majors modifications</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>Structure</head>
                        <p>In a scenario file, <gi>event</gi> elements are used as pointers to link
                            to full <gi>event</gi> elements stored in external files.</p>
                        <p>
                            <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                                <listEvent>
                                    <event xml:id="s1" type="step" ref="step_EaXswO_290517"/>
                                    <event xml:id="s2" type="step" ref="step_Eprimrf_300517"/>
                                    <event xml:id="s3" type="step" ref="step_Cad_300517"/>
                                    <event xml:id="s4" type="step" ref="step_Tdats_300517"/>
                                    <event xml:id="s5" type="step" ref="step_Sapditnf_300517"/>
                                </listEvent>
                            </egXML>
                        </p>
                        <p>It is also possible to refer to another scenario, that will be entirely
                            include in the described scenario. <egXML
                                xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                                <listEvent>
                                    <event type="scenario" ref="SSK_digitization.xml"/>
                                    <event xml:id="s1" type="step" ref="step_KedKep_170717"/> ...
                                </listEvent>
                            </egXML>
                        </p>
                        <p>However, it is possible to modify the content of a step directly in the
                            scenario file, for instance, modifying the label to contextualize it, or
                            adding a very specific resource. To do so, <gi>event</gi> and its
                            children can be specified with the <att>mode</att> attribute; with the
                            possible following values:<list>
                                <item>change</item>
                                <item>add</item>
                            </list>
                            <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                                <event type="step" ref="step_EaXswO_290517">
                                    <head mode="change">
                                        <label mode="change" xml:lang="jp">...</label>
                                        <term mode="add" type="standard"
                                            source="source of the vocabulary" key="newTerm"/>
                                    </head> ... </event>
                            </egXML>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <head>Complete events</head>
                    <p>A full description of the scenario step.</p>
                    <div>
                        <head>header</head>
                        <p>The structure of the step header is as follows:</p>
                        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                            <TEI type="step">
                                <teiHeader>
                                    <fileDesc>
                                        <titleStmt>
                                            <title><!-- title of the file, not title of the step --></title>
                                            <author>
                                                <persName>Charles Riondet</persName>
                                                <affiliation>Inria</affiliation>
                                            </author>
                                        </titleStmt>
                                        <publicationStmt>
                                            <authority>Parthenos</authority>
                                            <availability>
                                                <licence
                                                  target="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">
                                                  <p>The Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 Unported
                                                  (CC BY 4.0) Licence applies to this document.</p>
                                                </licence>
                                            </availability>
                                        </publicationStmt>
                                        <sourceDesc>
                                            <p>Created from scratch</p>
                                        </sourceDesc>
                                    </fileDesc>
                                    <revisionDesc>
                                        <change/>
                                    </revisionDesc>
                                </teiHeader> ... </TEI>
                        </egXML>
                        <p>The step header includes the following data elements: <list>
                                <item>the title of the document</item>
                                <item>the author of the step</item>
                                <item>the major modification</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>structure</head>
                        <p>The main elements of a <gi>event</gi> are the description of the event,
                            and the resources related to it. The description is recorded in the
                            element <gi>head</gi> (<ref target="#SSK_head">see below</ref>) and the
                            resources are contained by one or two <gi>listRef</gi> (<ref
                                target="#SSK_listRef">see below</ref>).</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div xml:id="SSK_term">
                    <head>term</head>
                    <p><gi>term</gi> elements are used to tag the scenarios, the steps and the
                        resources, according to the SSK taxonomies, that are:<list>
                            <item>The Tadirah activities</item>
                            <item>the Dariah Standard Knowledge base</item>
                        </list> These taxonomies are declared with the attributes <att>type</att>
                        and <att>source</att>. The attributes of <gi>term</gi> are <list>
                            <item>The <att>type</att> attribute gives an information about the kind
                                of term used. Its values are <list>
                                    <item>standard</item>
                                    <item>activity</item>
                                </list></item>
                            <item>The <att>source</att> attribute sets a reference link for the
                                taxonomy.</item>
                            <item>The <att>key</att> attribute gibes either an URI when the label of
                                the term can be taken from or directly a label</item>
                        </list>
                        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                            <term type="standard" source="standard_list" key="XML"/>
                        </egXML>
                        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                            <term type="activity" source="http://tadirah.dariah.eu/"
                                key="http://tadirah.dariah.eu/vocab/index.php?tema=22&amp;/annotating"
                            />
                        </egXML>
                    </p>

                </div>

                <div xml:id="SSK_head">
                    <head>head</head>
                    <p>The TEI <gi>head</gi> element: to record all the descriptive elements of a
                        scenario and a step. The <gi>label</gi>, the <gi>desc</gi>, the
                            <gi>term</gi>. See below.</p>
                    <p>
                        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                            <head>
                                <label xml:lang="en">Create associated documentation</label>
                                <label xml:lang="fr">Création de la documentation associée</label>
                                <desc xml:lang="en">To make you customization easy to read and
                                    understand by others, it is important to document all the
                                    changes made and present them clearly. ODD allows you to
                                    generate such documentation in various formats (HTML, PDF, Docx,
                                    etc.)</desc>
                                <term type="standard" source="standard_list" key="XML"/>
                                <term type="standard" source="standard_list" key="TEI"/>
                                <term type="standard" source="standard_list" key="EAD"/>
                                <term type="activity" source="http://tadirah.dariah.eu/"
                                    key="http://tadirah.dariah.eu/vocab/index.php?tema=22&amp;/annotating"
                                />
                            </head>
                        </egXML>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div xml:id="SSK_label">
                    <head>label</head>
                    <p>The attribute <att>xml:lang</att> is mandatory. The element <gi>label</gi>
                        can be repeated for give as many translated versions as possible.</p>
                    <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                        <label xml:lang="en">Create associated documentation</label>
                    </egXML>
                </div>
                <!-- to be replaced by linkGrp-->
                <div xml:id="SSK_listRef">
                    <head>listRef</head>
                    <p><gi>listRef</gi> is (for the moment) contained by the element <gi>ab</gi>.
                        The attribute <att>type</att> is required and can have two values:<list>
                            <item>general: for resources that give general input about a standard, a
                                protocol, ...</item>
                            <item>project: for resources that show examples of real projects using
                                the described standard, protocol, ...</item>
                        </list></p>
                    <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                        <ab>
                            <listRef type="general">
                                <ref type="spec" subtype="standard"
                                    target="http://zotero.org/groups/427927/items/QVUGK2B2"/>
                                <ref type="spec" subtype="standard"
                                    target="http://zotero.org/groups/427927/items/BEVAWMPX"/>
                            </listRef>
                            <listRef type="project">
                                <ref type="code" subtype="project" source="EHRI"
                                    target="https://github.com/EHRI/data-validations/blob/master/ODD-RelaxNG/EAD/EHRI_EAD_doc.html"/>
                                <ref type="report" subtype="copyBibl"
                                    target="step_Eprimf_3000517.xml#b1"/>
                            </listRef>
                        </ab>
                    </egXML>
                </div>
                <div xml:id="SSK_ref">
                    <head>ref</head>
                    <p>the attributes for <gi>ref</gi> are <att>type</att>, <att>subtype</att>,
                            <att>source</att> and <att>target</att>. <list>
                            <item>The values of <att>type</att> are the taken from the Zotero item
                                types, plus SSK specific values. Possible values are:<list>
                                    <item>spec: the specification, of a standard for
                                        instance.</item>
                                    <item>report: technical reports</item>
                                    <item>blog: blog posts</item>
                                    <item>tutorial: tutorials or guidelines</item>
                                    <item>script: Scripts and code samples</item>
                                    <item>paper: Scholarly papers</item>
                                </list></item>
                            <item>the <att>source</att> attribute in <gi>ref</gi> is used by the SSK
                                to record where the full information about the resource is stored,
                                and that the SSK queries. The values are a semi-closed list. The
                                    <att>source</att> attribute has for possible values:<list>
                                    <item>zotero: The Parthenos WP4 Zotero library: <ref
                                            target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/parthenos-wp4">WP4
                                            Zotero Library</ref></item>
                                    <item>github: resources hosted in a GitHub repository,
                                        preferably the <ref
                                            target="https://github.com/ParthenosWP4/standardsLibrary"
                                            >Parthenos WP4 repository</ref>, but not
                                        exclusively</item>
                                    <item>isidore: resources described in the platform of search
                                            <ref target="http://rechercheisidore.org">Isidore</ref>
                                        dedicated to Humanities and Social Sciences.</item>
                                    <item>pilastro: The Knowledge base describing Humanities and
                                        Social Sciences standards.</item>
                                    <!--<item>jrr</item>-->
                                </list></item>
                            <item>The <att>target</att> attribute specifies the destination of the
                                reference with an URI.</item>
                        </list>
                        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                            <ref type="spec" subtype="standard"
                                target="http://zotero.org/groups/427927/items/BEVAWMPX"/>
                        </egXML>
                    </p>
                </div>

            </div>
        </body>
